+{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CoVR7ULpSWTSZEZM4DJdUj","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good -- all 59 tests pass and TypeScript compiles cleanly. Now I have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Here is my complete review.\n\n---\n\n## Code Review: Document Management API\n\n### Overall Assessment\n\nThis is a well-structured implementation that meets all nine stated requirements. The code compiles cleanly, all 59 tests pass, and the overall architecture is sound. The separation into types, store, middleware, permissions, and per-domain route files is sensible and maintainable.\n\nThat said, I identified several issues ranging from a genuine correctness bug to important hardening gaps and code quality improvements. Below, I categorize each finding.\n\n---\n\n### CRITICAL Issues (Must Fix)\n\n#### 1. Incomplete circular reference check when moving folders (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 93-106)\n\nThe `PUT /folders/:id` endpoint prevents a folder from being set as its own parent (line 101: `parentId === folder.id`), but it does **not** detect deeper cycles. For example, given folders A -> B -> C, moving A to be a child of C would create A -> B -> C -> A, an infinite cycle. The `getEffectiveFolderRole` function in `/workspace/src/permissions.ts` recurses up the parent chain (line 99-100), so a circular folder structure would cause an **infinite loop and crash the server**.\n\n```typescript\n// /workspace/src/routes/folders.ts, lines 100-104\n// Only checks direct self-reference, not deeper cycles:\nif (parentId === folder.id) {\n  res.status(400).json({ error: 'Folder cannot be its own parent' });\n  return;\n}\n```\n\n**Recommendation**: Walk up the ancestor chain from the proposed `parentId` and verify the folder being moved does not appear as an ancestor of the target:\n\n```typescript\nfunction wouldCreateCycle(store: Store, folderId: string, proposedParentId: string): boolean {\n  let current: string | null = proposedParentId;\n  while (current) {\n    if (current === folderId) return true;\n    const folder = store.folders.get(current);\n    current = folder ? folder.parentId : null;\n  }\n  return false;\n}\n```\n\n#### 2. Recursive folder deletion does not clean up document shares (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 148-171)\n\nWhen `deleteFolderRecursive` deletes documents inside subfolders (lines 155-158), it removes the documents from the store but does **not** remove the corresponding share entries for those documents. The top-level delete handler (lines 137-139) only removes shares for the root folder being deleted, and `deleteFolderRecursive` only removes shares for subfolder entities. Any document-level shares are orphaned.\n\n```typescript\n// /workspace/src/routes/folders.ts, lines 153-170\nfor (const subfolder of subfolders) {\n  for (const [docId, doc] of store.documents.entries()) {\n    if (doc.folderId === subfolder.id) {\n      store.documents.delete(docId);\n      // BUG: shares referencing this document are never cleaned up\n    }\n  }\n  // ...\n  // Only folder shares are removed:\n  store.shares = store.shares.filter(\n    (s) => !(s.resourceType === 'folder' && s.resourceId === subfolder.id)\n  );\n}\n```\n\nSimilarly, the top-level delete handler deletes documents in the root folder (lines 126-130) but only cleans up folder-level shares for the root folder (lines 138-139), missing document shares for those documents.\n\n**Recommendation**: When deleting a document (whether in the recursive helper or the top-level handler), also filter out its shares:\n\n```typescript\nstore.shares = store.shares.filter(\n  (s) => !(s.resourceType === 'document' && s.resourceId === docId)\n);\n```\n\n---\n\n### IMPORTANT Issues (Should Fix)\n\n#### 3. Password stored in plain text (`/workspace/src/types.ts`, line 4; `/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, line 49)\n\nPasswords are stored as-is on the `User` object and compared with direct string equality. While this is an in-memory store not intended for production, the requirement calls for token-based auth, and storing plain-text passwords is a significant security anti-pattern even in prototypes. If any endpoint were to accidentally serialize a `User` object, the password would leak.\n\n**Recommendation**: At minimum, hash passwords with bcrypt or a similar library. As a lighter alternative, strip the `password` field from any user object before returning it in responses. Currently, the registration and login handlers carefully construct response objects (line 36 of auth.ts: `res.status(201).json({ id, username, token })`), so this is not actively leaking, but it remains a latent risk.\n\n#### 4. Token generation is cryptographically weak (`/workspace/src/store.ts`, line 19)\n\n```typescript\nexport function generateToken(): string {\n  return Math.random().toString(36).substring(2) + Date.now().toString(36);\n}\n```\n\n`Math.random()` is not cryptographically secure. Combined with the predictable `Date.now()` component, tokens are guessable if an attacker knows the approximate registration time.\n\n**Recommendation**: Use `crypto.randomBytes` or `crypto.randomUUID`:\n\n```typescript\nimport { randomBytes } from 'crypto';\nexport function generateToken(): string {\n  return randomBytes(32).toString('hex');\n}\n```\n\n#### 5. Activity log endpoint has no access control (`/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`, lines 9-27)\n\nAny authenticated user can read the entire activity log, including actions by other users on resources they have no access to. This leaks information about other users' private folders and documents (resource IDs, action types, timestamps, and share details).\n\n```typescript\n// /workspace/src/routes/activity.ts, line 9\nrouter.get('/activity', requireAuth, (req: AuthRequest, res) => {\n  // No filtering by user permissions - returns everything\n  let logs = [...store.activityLog];\n```\n\n**Recommendation**: Filter activity entries to only those where the requesting user has at least viewer access to the referenced resource, or is the actor. Alternatively, scope the endpoint to the current user's own actions.\n\n#### 6. Editor can grant editor role, enabling privilege escalation (`/workspace/src/routes/sharing.ts`, lines 58-68)\n\nThe sharing logic requires `editor` permission to share as `viewer` or `editor`, and `owner` permission to share as `owner`. This means an editor can grant other users the same editor role they have. While this may be intentional, it means a single editor share can create an unbounded number of new editors -- effectively making the `editor` role self-propagating. This is worth a deliberate design decision.\n\n#### 7. Duplicate code across three sharing routes (`/workspace/src/routes/sharing.ts`)\n\nThe `POST /share`, `POST /folders/:id/share`, and `POST /documents/:id/share` endpoints duplicate approximately 60 lines of validation and share-creation logic each. This is the largest DRY violation in the codebase. If a business rule changes (e.g., adding a \"revoke\" check), it must be updated in three places.\n\n**Recommendation**: Extract a shared `handleShare(store, currentUser, resourceType, resourceId, userId, role)` function and call it from all three route handlers.\n\n#### 8. `GET /folders/:id` returns subfolders/documents without permission filtering (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`, lines 60-67)\n\nWhen a user views a folder, all subfolders and documents are returned, even if the user does not have permission to access some of them. For example, if a subfolder was created by a different user and not shared, it still appears in the listing.\n\n```typescript\nconst subfolders = Array.from(store.folders.values()).filter(\n  (f) => f.parentId === folder.id\n);\nconst documents = Array.from(store.documents.values()).filter(\n  (d) => d.folderId === folder.id\n);\n```\n\n**Recommendation**: Filter both `subfolders` and `documents` arrays through `hasPermission` before returning them, so users only see items they have access to.\n\n---\n\n### SUGGESTIONS (Nice to Have)\n\n#### 9. No activity logging for folder CRUD operations (`/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts`)\n\nDocument create/update/delete and sharing events are logged, but folder create/update/delete events are not logged at all. This is an inconsistency -- the activity log is incomplete.\n\n#### 10. Login generates a new token, invalidating previous sessions (`/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, lines 51-52)\n\nEach login replaces the token in-place, which invalidates any other session using the old token. This is a design choice, but it means a user cannot be logged in from two clients simultaneously. If that is intentional, it should be documented.\n\n#### 11. Linear scan for token lookup (`/workspace/src/middleware.ts`, lines 15-19)\n\nThe auth middleware iterates over all users for every request to find a matching token. For an in-memory prototype this is acceptable, but a `Map<string, User>` keyed by token would provide O(1) lookups.\n\n#### 12. `nextId` counter is shared across all entity types (`/workspace/src/store.ts`)\n\nUsers, folders, documents, shares, and activity entries all share a single incrementing counter. While this guarantees uniqueness, it produces non-contiguous IDs within each entity type and makes the ID sequence leak information about overall system activity. Separate counters per entity type would be cleaner.\n\n#### 13. No pagination on activity log or folder listings\n\nBoth `GET /activity` and `GET /folders/:id` return all matching entries. For a growing dataset, this will eventually cause performance problems. Consider adding `limit` and `offset` query parameters.\n\n#### 14. Test coverage gaps\n\nThe 59 tests cover the main flows well, but some notable scenarios are missing:\n- Moving a folder to create a circular chain (the critical bug in item 1)\n- Verifying that deleting a folder also cleans up document shares\n- Multi-level permission inheritance (grandparent -> parent -> child -> document)\n- Concurrent token invalidation after re-login\n- Empty string or whitespace-only folder names and document titles\n\n---\n\n### What Was Done Well\n\n- **Clean architecture**: The factory function pattern (`createApp`, `createStore`, `create*Router`) makes testing straightforward and avoids global mutable state. Each test gets a fresh app instance via `beforeEach`.\n- **Permission inheritance logic**: The recursive `getEffectiveFolderRole` function in `/workspace/src/permissions.ts` correctly walks up the folder hierarchy and the \"most permissive wins\" semantic is correctly implemented using the `ROLE_HIERARCHY` map.\n- **Input validation**: Routes consistently validate required fields, check types, and return appropriate HTTP status codes (400, 401, 403, 404, 409).\n- **Type safety**: TypeScript strict mode is enabled, the code compiles without errors, and the types in `/workspace/src/types.ts` accurately represent the domain model.\n- **Test organization**: The test file is well-structured with clear describe blocks, good helper functions, and meaningful test descriptions. The 59 tests cover auth, CRUD, sharing, permissions, activity logging, and edge cases.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | File | Issue |\n|---|----------|------|-------|\n| 1 | Critical | `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts` | Incomplete cycle detection allows infinite loops |\n| 2 | Critical | `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts` | Recursive delete orphans document shares |\n| 3 | Important | `/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts`, `/workspace/src/types.ts` | Plain-text password storage |\n| 4 | Important | `/workspace/src/store.ts` | Weak token generation |\n| 5 | Important | `/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts` | Activity log leaks all users' data |\n| 6 | Important | `/workspace/src/routes/sharing.ts` | Editor role is self-propagating |\n| 7 | Important | `/workspace/src/routes/sharing.ts` | Three sharing routes duplicate ~180 lines |\n| 8 | Important | `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts` | Folder listing returns unfiltered children |\n| 9 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes/folders.ts` | No activity logging for folder operations |\n| 10 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes/auth.ts` | Login invalidates previous sessions |\n| 11 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/middleware.ts` | Linear scan for token lookup |\n| 12 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/store.ts` | Shared ID counter across entity types |\n| 13 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/routes/activity.ts`, `folders.ts` | No pagination |\n| 14 | Suggestion | `/workspace/src/app.test.ts` | Missing test scenarios for critical bugs |\n\nItems 1 and 2 are correctness bugs that should be fixed before considering this implementation complete. Items 3-8 are hardening and code quality issues that deserve attention in any near-term iteration."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a078cf4 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 38780\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 86556</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6e31066c-a8ad-4667-833e-bf0517b50028","uuid":"de12cd2a-4e40-4be9-b84a-c3effddba8cc","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the implementation of the document management API. The implementation includes:\n\n- src/types.ts - Type definitions\n- src/store.ts - In-memory storage\n- src/middleware.ts - Auth middleware\n- src/permissions.ts - Permission checking logic\n- src/routes/auth.ts - Auth routes (register/login)\n- src/routes/folders.ts - Folder CRUD\n- src/routes/documents.ts - Document CRUD\n- src/routes/sharing.ts - Sharing routes\n- src/routes/activity.ts - Activity log\n- src/app.ts - Main app (createApp)\n- src/app.test.ts - Tests (59 tests, all passing)\n\nRequirements:\n1. Express API with createApp() export\n2. User registration and login with token auth\n3. Folder CRUD with nesting\n4. Document CRUD in folders\n5. Sharing with viewer/editor/owner roles\n6. Permiss